@galopin Yes, completely agree we should fix this.  We just need to be careful to not fix this while unintentionally breaking other people as a result of this change.

@JordonPhillips To elaborate on my point more, while file system encoding in general is flaky, I don't think we can always assume it's utf-8.  Additionally, failure to decode to unicode when we can't load a config shouldn't itself be a failure, even using replacement chars seems to be better than failing on a decode in this specific scenario.

So my suggestion:

1. Move the decoding into the configloader module when we raise an exception.
2. Use similar logic to what the S3 code in the CLI uses (`sys.getfilesystemencoding()` I think).
3. Use `'replace'` when decoding so it's not a hard failure (I don't think we want to mask the original error message if we can't decode the file).

